Compliance, Privacy, and Ethical Safeguards:

PHI Handling and HIPAA Controls:
  - All youth behavioral data is Protected Health Information (PHI) under HIPAA.
  - Data at rest is encrypted using AES-256 in Firestore via Google Cloud default encryption.
  - Data in transit uses TLS 1.2 or higher for all API calls.
  - Role-based access control: direct care staff may read and write DPN records for their assigned youth only; case managers may access all records for their caseload; clinical supervisors and admins have facility-wide read access. Roles are defined in the `user_roles` Firestore collection.
  - Audit logging: every read and write to a youth record logs the authenticated user ID, timestamp, action type, and record ID to a tamper-evident Firestore audit collection.
  - Retention policy: active youth records are retained indefinitely during enrollment. Records of discharged youth are retained for 7 years post-discharge per state licensing requirements, then deleted or de-identified per a documented destruction procedure.

Informed Consent:
  - The risk assessment and AI-assisted pattern recognition (see sections 1 and 3 above) are disclosed to guardians and youth (where age-appropriate) during the admission intake process via the facility consent form.
  - Consent records are stored in the youth's legal record and linked to their Firestore profile.
  - Guardians may request that AI-generated narrative comments not be used; in that case, staff must write all comments manually. This preference is flagged in the youth profile.

Mandatory Human Clinical Oversight:
  - AI outputs (DPN comments, risk summaries, behavioral alerts) are advisory only. No AI output is applied to a youth's record without staff action.
  - AI-assisted pattern recognition alerts (Trigger 1–4 above) require documented clinical acknowledgment before the alert is dismissed.
  - Automatic demotion triggers (Level Progression Engine, section 2) require licensed clinician sign-off before demotion is applied.
  - Level-based privilege management changes require case manager approval and are logged with the approving user's ID and timestamp.

Bias and Fairness Controls:
  - Risk Assessment scores (section 3) are reviewed quarterly at the population level, stratified by age and race/ethnicity as documented, to detect disparate impact.
  - Disparate-impact testing threshold: if any subgroup's mean risk score differs from the facility-wide mean by more than 10 points without a documented clinical explanation, the scoring formula is reviewed by the clinical director.
  - Bias audit results and any remediation steps are documented in the annual compliance report.
  - Demographic attributes (race, ethnicity, religion) are excluded from all AI model inputs.

Youth Rights and Appeals:
  - Any youth or guardian may request a printed summary of the youth's current DPN scores, risk level, and level standing at any time.
  - Corrections: if a score is believed to be entered in error, the youth or guardian may request a review by the clinical supervisor within 30 days. The supervisor may amend the record; all amendments are logged with the original value, new value, timestamp, and authorizing clinician.
  - Youth are actively involved in treatment planning: DPN scores and level progress are reviewed with the youth at least weekly during structured meetings.

Incident Reporting and External Audit:
  - A qualified independent reviewer conducts an annual audit of the behavioral scoring system, reviewing a random sample of DPN records, risk scores, and level changes for accuracy and compliance.
  - HIPAA breach reporting: any unauthorized disclosure of PHI triggers immediate notification to the facility director; breaches affecting fewer than 500 individuals are logged in the annual breach report to HHS OCR; breaches affecting 500 or more individuals require notification to HHS OCR and prominent media outlets within 60 days.
  - Score change audit trail: every DPN score change, risk score recalculation, level change, and demotion is logged with a timestamp and the user ID of the initiating staff member. This log is immutable and available for inspection by authorized auditors.

The behavioral scoring system implements specialized youth treatment facility metrics with emphasis on:
- Multi-domain behavioral assessment
- AI-assisted pattern recognition (see sections 1 and 3 for model documentation and oversight controls)
- Risk-based intervention triggers (see section 4 for specific trigger rules and authorization model)
- Level-based privilege management (see section 2 for level table, demotion criteria, and appeals process)

